          "title": "Divine silence — the chapter's theological verdict on Saul",
          "body": "Verse 37 is the chapter's climax and the narrator's most damning detail: 'But He did not answer him on that day.' Saul's formal inquiry — through the proper priestly channel, using the Urim and Thummim (v. 41) — meets absolute silence. God had spoken all day through Jonathan's faith; He refuses to speak to the king's formal consultation. The interpreter must resist the temptation to soften this. Divine silence is communicative. In the Old Testament, God's silence in response to inquiry signals that something has blocked the communication — unconfessed sin (Ps. 66:18), presumption, or the presence of someone under judgment (cf. 1 Sam. 28:6, where the silence about Saul persists into the necromancer episode). The lot-casting that follows (vv. 40-42) reveals Jonathan as the technical violator of the oath, but the chapter has already established that Jonathan ate in ignorance (v. 27). The silence was about Saul's oath, not Jonathan's honey."
